@node intro "Introduction"

 Introduction
 ------------

    IceFileSort is an arexx script for IceBBS Sysop's to help (and in my case
saves 3-4 hours of work a week!) with file maintanence of Aminet files. The
IceBBS file type which it uses is an aminet file with the .readme file in the
IceBBS header.
    Basically, what the script will do for you is move files from a directory
(via an assign) to appropriate places which you specify on your hard drive. As
you can see, having a script automatically moving x number of files instead of
having to look at the file description, think of where they should go on the HD
and then move them across will save a lot of time. In my case, about 2/3 of all
files are now moved via the script. Yesterday I downloaded 17 megs of new files
from Aminet, and 14 Megs today! <From overnight-uploads to Aminet> As you can
imagine, this is a fair number of files!

PLEASE NOTE! This program was originally intended to be written in C, but on
advice from a friend, I used Arexx. I have never programmed in arexx in my
life, and only had 3 arexx scripts to which I could try to understand to code
this script. It is probably the worst & messiest script you wil lhave ever
seen, and can be optimised in many many ways. At the moment, it is about 10x
faster than what it originally was. Its usable. On my machine (030/50) it went
throuh 340 files in 5 mintutes. That was a build up of about 1-2 months of new
files! I will optimise it when I find out how, and will release newer versions
on aminet. Keep an eye out!

@endnode

@node why "Why?"

 Why write IceFileSort?
 ----------------------

    Basically, apart from moving lots of files quickly, the Aminet directory
structure isnt practical for BBS's. ie, a picture viewer that is in pix/show
would be more applicable in Graphics:Picture_viewers/ or something like that on
a BBS. The IceFileSort script takes care of all this by using the
@{"IceFileSort" link IceSortDir} file.

@endnode

@node requirements "IceFileSort requirements"

IceFileSort requires Arexx (wb 2.0+), the following AmigaDOS
commands:

delete
dir
execute
list
move

And the command "Append" from the full IceBBS package (by Stephen Vermeulen.) 

Make sure all these files are pathed, ie, "append" is available in c: or any
other pathed directory.

An Assign "IceFileDir:" is needed to the directory you want the script to
operate, and an assign "BBS:" is required for the IceSortDir file.

@endnode

@node Usage "IceFileSort Usage"

 Usage
 -----

Note: To make files so you can use IceFileSort, read the last part of this
section.

Usage: rx icefilesort.rx

Icefilesort looks into the directory/assign "BBS:" for the file @{"IceSortDir"
link IceSortDir}
and also looks for the assign "IceFileDir:" for the BBS files to be moved.

When the script is running, you will be told how many 'comparison' files there
are in the IceSortDir file, and how many files there are in the "IceFileDir:"
assign. It will then go through each file in the list one at a time, and will
tell you if the aminet "Type:" word is found in the first 10 lines of the file.
If it is, it looks in the IceSortDir file for the aminet subdir. If it is
found, the file will be added to the script in ram, and if it isnt found you
will be notified and the file added to a list in ram.

Once IceFileDir has finished its work, you will find 2 files in Ram:

MoveIceFiles
UnknownFiles

The first file, an AmigaDos script MoveIceFiles, will move the files it found
with equivalent dirs in the @{"comparison" link IceSortDir} file.  Note that
there are a couple of restrictions with filenames.  These can be seen in the
@{"Restrictions" link restictions} section.

Type: execute ram:MoveIceFiles

and the script will be run

The second file, UnknownFiles, contains a list of all the files in the assign
"BBS:" that were aminet files with .readme's in the header, but no equivalent
direcory in the IceSortDir comparison file.  This is so you can see what files
wont be moved and also what repective aminet directories the files are from.
THis can help when adding dirs to the IceSortDir comparison file.


Making integrated .readme and IceBBS files
------------------------------------------

    The way I quickly and easily make the files is by the following way:

1) Download Aminet files with their respective .readme's
2) Convert to LZX (optional)
3) Use the IceBBS 'AmiJoin' command. This will join the aminet files with their
readmes in an IceBBS file, with the Short: of the aminet as the Short
description of the file, and the whole .readme as the long description.
4) Copy the files into NewFiles: .
5) Move all files over about 2 weeks old to a temporary dir.
6) Run the IceFileSort script every few days or whenever to move a lot of the
files quickly and easily to their proper dirs on the Hard Drive.

Simple, quick, efficent and brilliant.

@endnode

@node IceSortDir "The IceSortDir file"

 The IceSortDir file
 -------------------

Is looked for in an assign "BBS:"

The IceSortDir file is a simple file containing text which IceFileSort
requires. There are 2 pieces of text in each line: The first is an aminet-dir
(eg: pix/show, util/boot) and the second is the path to the dir on your HD.
(eg, could be Graphics:viewers or Utilities:Boot_programs). Note there are
@{"Restrictions" link restrictions} on filenames. You can have spaces in the
list if you like, but it is faster if you dont have them. No order is
neccessary, although it is easier to see if you have a dir in there already.

I have included my own IcefileSort file for you to edit. 

Basically, it is a comparison or equivalent-making file.

@endnode


@node restrictions "IceFileSort Restrictions"

 Restictions
 -----------

- Filenames in the assign "IceFileDir:" must have no spaces.
- The destination directory must have no spaces
    (Due to being unable to echo quotes)


@endnode

@node Problems "Problem Solving"

Following is a list of problems and possible answers, that arise from using the
script :-

Prob: When running the script, "Move cannot locate file <filename>" or similar.
Answer: The move command does not seem to like having '/' at the end of a dir.
        Go into your IceSortDir file and locate the directory that the problem 
        is occuring in, and remove the end '/'.

Prob: When running the IceFileSort rexx script, the program breaks and says
      "Cant find file <something>".
Answer: The filename it is trying to locate has a space in it. Remove the space
        and try again.

Prob: When running the IceFileSort rexx scrip, it locates a file with a "Type:"
      and attempts to find the aminet-subdir in the IceSortDir file, but says
      it cant find it, even though you KNOW it is there!
Answer: Load up Ced (or your favourite text editor) and load the file with the
        problem. Check the aminet-subdir after "Type:". You will probably find
        that the sub-dir is something like util/boot<ctrl-M>! This is probably
        due to the uploader probably using a PC which has funny text formatting.
        So how do you get round it? Simple, just add a line in your IceFileDir
        script with the exact representation of what is in the file (eg:
        util/boot<control-m>). This will solve the problem for that file and
        any other file that has a wierd aminet-subdir.

@endnode    

